39.71	Anna_Leonowens	Anna Leonowens	Anna Leonowens (26 November 1831 â€“ 19 January 1915) was an English travel writer, educator, and social activist. She worked in Siam from 1862 to 1868, where she taught the wives and children of Mongkut, king of Siam. She also co-founded the Nova Scotia College of Art and Design. Leonowens's experiences in Siam were fictionalised in Margaret Landon's 1944 bestselling novel Anna and the King of Siam and in various films and television miniseries based on the book, most notably Rodgers and Hammerstein's 1951 hit musical The King and I.	http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/e/e8/Leonowens_Portrait.jpg
